Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(thinly sliced).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Coarsely grate the @apple{1}(coarsely grated).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) and @ginger{1}(peeled and grated) (use a teaspoon to easily scrape away the peel).

Place a #large pot{} over medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the @North Indian Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and @curry powder{1%sachet} and cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the garlic, onion and ginger and cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the lentils and apple to the #pot{} and mix well to combine.

Stir in the @coconut milk{1%pack} along with @water{200%ml} (double for 4p).

Reduce the heat and cook the dahl, covered, for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Remove the lid and allow to cook until lentils are tender, a further ~{5%minutes}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> TIP: Loosen the curry with a splash of water if it becomes too dry.

When 5 mins of cooking time remain for the dahl, sprinkle the @naan{2} with a little water.

Pop into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{5%g}(leaves picked and roughly chopped).

Quarter the @lime{1}(quartered).

In the final 2 mins of cooking, add the @peas{120%g} to the dahl.

Stir to combine and allow to warm through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Finish the dahl with a squeeze of lime juice.

Divide the dahl between #bowls{} and garnish with a sprinkling of mint.

Serve with naan and remaining lime wedges alongside.